A lightweight and flexible Linux distribution that tries to "Keep It Simple", for Fydetab Duo. The official release of Arch Linux for the Fydetab Duo is now available, fully ready to use right out of the box. This version features the KDE Plasma desktop as the default, providing a sleek and efficient user experience.

Details Build: preview1-20221219 Release noteâ€‹ Hightlight Initial release of Arch Linux port for Fydetab Duo. Useful things to note: Default login credentials: alarm/root: alarm Using iwd to connect to the internet: This release of Arch Linux does not bundle with a default Desktop Environment, if you want one, you need to install it yourself Known issues It's still in the early porting stage; the following features are still under development: Desktop Environment UI is still software rendering, hardware acceleration is unavailable Download linksâ€‹ Direct link Mirror link SHA256: 71b1cf3c6fa4aea650c877eb9fd91eaeb179b53562a534eebce69abe7766570a ğŸ“š Tutorial: Installing KDE Plasma Desktopâ€‹ This is an initial test installation guide for the Fydetab Duo. In this tutorial, we cover some basic steps to: Connect to Wi-Fi ğŸ”§ Flash Image Under Linuxâ€‹ Assuming: The Fydetab Duo is connected and in loader mode (see Fydetab Duo Wiki). The upgrade_tool is located under ./foundation-rk3588/rk3588-image-maker/Linux_Upgrade_Tool/upgrade_tool. The SHA256 sum validated, extracted fydetab_duo-archlinux-update-20221219.img image is in the current folder: sudo ./foundation-rk3588/rk3588-image-maker/Linux_Upgrade_Tool/upgrade_tool uf ./fydetab_duo-archlinux-update-20221219.img âš ï¸ Warning: Serious neck stiffness possible as the tty is not rotatable with: echo 3 > /sys/class/graphics/fbcon/rotate_all Login with: Username: root Password: alarm Double your tty font size: setfont -d ğŸŒ Set Up Your Wi-Fi (WLAN0)â€‹ Follow the instructions under Arch Linux Wiki - Iwd. Start by adding some required configuration details: mkdir /etc/iwd nano /etc/iwd/main.conf Insert: [General] EnableNetworkConfiguration=true [Network] EnableIPv6=true (If you don't have/want IPv6, set EnableIPv6=false) Enable the Iwd network service: systemctl enable --now iwd Edit the connection details with: iwctl If you do not know your wireless device name, list all Wi-Fi devices: [iwd]# device list the name for your Wi-Fi device should be listed as wlan0, Adapter should be phy0 If the device or its corresponding adapter is turned off, turn it on: [iwd]# device wlan0 set-property Powered on [iwd]# adapter phy0 set-property Powered on Initiate a scan for networks (this command will not output anything): [iwd]# station wlan0 scan List all available networks: [iwd]# station wlan0 get-networks Connect to a network: [iwd]# station wlan0 connect SSID Exit iwctl with crtl + d Check if your wlan0 device now has an IP address: ip --brief address show ğŸ’¡ Hint: Now you should be able to access the device via SSH... ğŸ§© Resize the Root Partitionâ€‹ In this tutorial, only one root partition is available and used, limited to 12 GB. Increase the size of the root partition to the available space (12 GB), as the image comes with only 2 GB of preconfigured available space: resize2fs /dev/mmcblk0p1 ğŸ”„ Install Updatesâ€‹ Adapt sources.list: nano /etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist Select a fitting mirror near your location and update with the Arch package manager pacman: pacman -Syyu Accept the defaults when prompted. During the update, kernel-related files may trigger warnings as they cannot be found and are likely not part of the Arch installation (supplied via image, kernel 5.10 is installed). Check the kernel via: uname -a Expected output: Linux alarm 5.10.110-fyde #145 SMP Mon Dec 19 07:00:43 UTC 2022 aarch64 GNU/Linux Reboot: shutdown -r 0 Set your local timeâ€‹ in /usr/share/zoneinfo there are all possible locations listed. You can set your local time via e.g. ln -s /usr/share/zoneinfo/Europe/Berlin /etc/localtime Set your language preference / localeâ€‹ select one or more locales in /etc/locale.gen. afterwards execute locale-gen enable the primarly locale via e.g. localectl set-locale LANG=en_US.UTF-8 otherwise, you can also check and uncomment any available locale in /etc/locale.gen ğŸ–¥ï¸ Install KDE Plasmaâ€‹ Follow the instructions at Arch Linux Wiki - KDE. As of July 2024, this will install Plasma 6.1. Install KDE Plasma, display manager, KScreen for display adjustment, Bluetooth, and PackageKit for "Discover" software management integration xorg-xrandr for SDDM screen rotation: pacman -S plasma-meta sddm sddm-kcm kscreen bluez bluez-utils packagekit, xorg-xrandr Accept the defaults when prompted or adjust options to your preference. To adjust screen rotation in SDDM, edit /usr/share/sddm/scripts/Xsetup, and add xrandr -o right in /var/lib/sddm/state.conf, you have to add [Last] # Name of the last logged-in user. # This user will be preselected when the login screen appears User=alarm # Name of the session for the last logged-in user. # This session will be preselected when the login screen appears. Session=/usr/share/xsessions/plasmax11.desktop [X11] DisplayCommand=/usr/share/sddm/scripts/Xsetup Start and enable SDDM and Bluetooth: systemctl enable --now sddm bluetooth A reboot may be required. You will now be greeted by the Plasma SDDM login screen. Currently, as per the configuration above, X11 is preselected. Wayland sessions will only show a black screen. Once logged in (initial password alarm), you can adjust the Plasma desktop settings to rotate. Additional software can now be installed via Discover. ğŸ“ TODOâ€‹ As this is a very limited environment still, some tasks need to be done, both for the user and on the hardware support, which is limited by the shipped Linux kernel: Partitioning: only 2 GB root partition, resized to 12 GB. Additional partitioning required & files need moving. Rotate tty. Replace Iwd. Wayland does not run yet. Hardware: Bluetooth & camera don't work -> kernel build + kernel modules for Bluetooth, but how? Hardware: Display is only software rendering supported -> kernel build + kernel modules for display, but how? Hardware: Other hardware e.g., accelerometer, NPU ...

Hightlight Initial release of Arch Linux port for Fydetab Duo. Useful things to note: Default login credentials: alarm/root: alarm Using iwd to connect to the internet: This release of Arch Linux does not bundle with a default Desktop Environment, if you want one, you need to install it yourself Known issues It's still in the early porting stage; the following features are still under development: Desktop Environment UI is still software rendering, hardware acceleration is unavailable

The SHA256 sum validated, extracted fydetab_duo-archlinux-update-20221219.img image is in the current folder: sudo ./foundation-rk3588/rk3588-image-maker/Linux_Upgrade_Tool/upgrade_tool uf ./fydetab_duo-archlinux-update-20221219.img âš ï¸ Warning: Serious neck stiffness possible as the tty is not rotatable with: echo 3 > /sys/class/graphics/fbcon/rotate_all Login with: Username: root Password: alarm Double your tty font size: setfont -d

Follow the instructions under Arch Linux Wiki - Iwd. Start by adding some required configuration details: mkdir /etc/iwd nano /etc/iwd/main.conf Insert: [General] EnableNetworkConfiguration=true [Network] EnableIPv6=true (If you don't have/want IPv6, set EnableIPv6=false) Enable the Iwd network service: systemctl enable --now iwd Edit the connection details with: iwctl If you do not know your wireless device name, list all Wi-Fi devices: [iwd]# device list the name for your Wi-Fi device should be listed as wlan0, Adapter should be phy0 If the device or its corresponding adapter is turned off, turn it on: [iwd]# device wlan0 set-property Powered on [iwd]# adapter phy0 set-property Powered on Initiate a scan for networks (this command will not output anything): [iwd]# station wlan0 scan List all available networks: [iwd]# station wlan0 get-networks Connect to a network: [iwd]# station wlan0 connect SSID Exit iwctl with crtl + d Check if your wlan0 device now has an IP address: ip --brief address show ğŸ’¡ Hint: Now you should be able to access the device via SSH...

In this tutorial, only one root partition is available and used, limited to 12 GB. Increase the size of the root partition to the available space (12 GB), as the image comes with only 2 GB of preconfigured available space: resize2fs /dev/mmcblk0p1

Adapt sources.list: nano /etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist Select a fitting mirror near your location and update with the Arch package manager pacman: pacman -Syyu Accept the defaults when prompted. During the update, kernel-related files may trigger warnings as they cannot be found and are likely not part of the Arch installation (supplied via image, kernel 5.10 is installed). Check the kernel via: uname -a Expected output: Linux alarm 5.10.110-fyde #145 SMP Mon Dec 19 07:00:43 UTC 2022 aarch64 GNU/Linux Reboot: shutdown -r 0
in /usr/share/zoneinfo there are all possible locations listed. You can set your local time via e.g. ln -s /usr/share/zoneinfo/Europe/Berlin /etc/localtime

select one or more locales in /etc/locale.gen. afterwards execute locale-gen enable the primarly locale via e.g. localectl set-locale LANG=en_US.UTF-8 otherwise, you can also check and uncomment any available locale in /etc/locale.gen

Follow the instructions at Arch Linux Wiki - KDE. As of July 2024, this will install Plasma 6.1. Install KDE Plasma, display manager, KScreen for display adjustment, Bluetooth, and PackageKit for "Discover" software management integration xorg-xrandr for SDDM screen rotation: pacman -S plasma-meta sddm sddm-kcm kscreen bluez bluez-utils packagekit, xorg-xrandr Accept the defaults when prompted or adjust options to your preference. To adjust screen rotation in SDDM, edit /usr/share/sddm/scripts/Xsetup, and add xrandr -o right in /var/lib/sddm/state.conf, you have to add [Last] # Name of the last logged-in user. # This user will be preselected when the login screen appears User=alarm # Name of the session for the last logged-in user. # This session will be preselected when the login screen appears. Session=/usr/share/xsessions/plasmax11.desktop [X11] DisplayCommand=/usr/share/sddm/scripts/Xsetup Start and enable SDDM and Bluetooth: systemctl enable --now sddm bluetooth A reboot may be required. You will now be greeted by the Plasma SDDM login screen. Currently, as per the configuration above, X11 is preselected. Wayland sessions will only show a black screen. Once logged in (initial password alarm), you can adjust the Plasma desktop settings to rotate. Additional software can now be installed via Discover.

As this is a very limited environment still, some tasks need to be done, both for the user and on the hardware support, which is limited by the shipped Linux kernel: Partitioning: only 2 GB root partition, resized to 12 GB. Additional partitioning required & files need moving. Rotate tty. Replace Iwd. Wayland does not run yet. Hardware: Bluetooth & camera don't work -> kernel build + kernel modules for Bluetooth, but how? Hardware: Display is only software rendering supported -> kernel build + kernel modules for display, but how? Hardware: Other hardware e.g., accelerometer, NPU ...
